### 2022

As of the 2022 [American Community Survey](/American_Community_Survey) estimates, Long Beach had a population of 451,319 people living in 170,965 households. The [population density](/Population_density) was a crowded 8,906.7 inhabitants per square mile. The city's racial makeup was 34.6% [White](/White_American), 11.8% [Black or African American](/African_American), 12.5% [Asian](/Asian_American), 1.8% [Native American or Alaskan Native](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States), 1.0% [Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander](/Pacific_Islander_Americans), 20.1% from some other race, and 18.2% from two or more races. [Hispanics or Latinos](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans) of any race constituted 44.0% of the population.

The median household income was $80,493, with a [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) of $41,896. However, 13.8% of the population lived below the [poverty line](/Poverty_line), a figure that underscores the economic disparities within the city.

