### Retail

While no longer the retail powerhouse it was in the mid-20th century, Long Beach still maintains several shopping centers. The largest is the [Long Beach Towne Center](/Long_Beach_Towne_Center), a sprawling power center built on the site of the former Naval Hospital. Downtown has seen a resurgence with developments like The Pike Outlets.

## Arts and culture

### Art

The city's art scene is anchored by institutions like the [Long Beach Museum of Art](/Long_Beach_Museum_of_Art) and the [Museum of Latin American Art](/Museum_of_Latin American_Art) (MOLAA), the only museum in the western U.S. dedicated exclusively to modern and contemporary Latin American art. The Pacific Island Ethnic Art Museum (PieAM) celebrates the arts and cultures of Oceania.

Long Beach is particularly known for its vibrant [street art](/Street_art). [Murals](/Mural) adorn buildings throughout the city, some officially sanctioned, others not. The exterior of the [Long Beach Sports Arena](/Long_Beach_Sports_Arena) features one of artist [Wyland's](/Robert_Wyland) massive "[Whaling Walls](/List_of_Whaling_Walls)," which, at 116,000 square feet, is the world's largest mural according to the [Guinness Book of Records](/Guinness_Book_of_Records). The [East Village Arts District](/Long_Beach_East_Village) is a hub for galleries and artists, hosting a monthly Artwalk.

### Music

The city has a rich and eclectic music scene. The [Bob Cole Conservatory of Music](/Bob_Cole_Conservatory_of_Music) at CSULB is a major center for classical and jazz performance. The [Long Beach Symphony](/Long_Beach_Symphony_Orchestra) and [Long Beach Opera](/Long_Beach_Opera) offer professional performances. The local public radio station, [KJAZZ](/KKJZ) 88.1 FM, broadcasts from the CSULB campus.

Long Beach has been a breeding ground for influential artists across numerous genres, including hip-hop legends like [Snoop Dogg](/Snoop_Dogg) and [Warren G](/Warren_G), the genre-bending band [Sublime](/Sublime_(band)), and contemporary artists like [Vince Staples](/Vince_Staples) and [Frank Ocean](/Frank_Ocean).

### Theater

Long Beach supports a robust theater community, from large regional producers like Musical Theatre West to smaller, more experimental companies like The Garage Theatre. The historic [Art Theatre](/Art_Theatre) on the [4th Street Corridor](/4th_Street_Corridor) is a cherished local landmark.

### Cultural events

The city's calendar is packed with events that reflect its diversity. The [Grand Prix of Long Beach](/Grand_Prix_of_Long_Beach) brings the roar of race cars downtown every April. The Long Beach Lesbian and Gay Pride Parade and Festival, held since 1984, is the second-largest event in the city and one of the largest Pride celebrations in the country. The "Naples Island Christmas Parade" of decorated boats has been a holiday tradition since 1946.

## Sites of interest

*   **RMS Queen Mary:** A 1936 [Art Deco](/Art_Deco) ocean liner, permanently docked and serving as a hotel, museum, and, according to many, a residence for ghosts. The city purchased it in 1967, and it has been both a beloved landmark and a financial burden ever since.
*   **[Aquarium of the Pacific](/Aquarium_of_the_Pacific):** A world-class aquarium on Rainbow Harbor, showcasing the marine life of the Pacific Ocean.
*   **[Rancho Los Alamitos](/Rancho_Los_Alamitos)** and **[Rancho Los Cerritos](/Rancho_Los_Cerritos):** Two historic sites that offer a glimpse into the area's Spanish and Mexican rancho past, preserved islands of adobe and gardens amidst the modern city.
*   **[Earl Burns Miller Japanese Garden](/Earl_Burns_Miller_Japanese_Garden):** A serene oasis on the campus of [California State University, Long Beach](/California_State_University,_Long_Beach).
*   **Gondola Rides:** In a surreal nod to Venice, singing [gondoliers](/Gondola) navigate the canals of the [Naples](/Naples,_Long_Beach,_California) neighborhood.

## Parks and recreation

For a city so thoroughly urbanized, Long Beach has an impressive park system, managing 92 parks covering over 3,100 acres. The crown jewel is the 815-acre [El Dorado Regional Park](/El_Dorado_Regional_Park), a massive green space with fishing lakes, bike trails, and a nature center. The city has also made efforts to restore natural habitats, such as the [Los Cerritos Wetlands](/Los_Cerritos_Wetlands) and the [Long Beach Green Belt path](/Long_Beach_Green_Belt_path), a stretch of the old Pacific Electric right-of-way reclaimed as native habitat. Rosie's Dog Beach in [Belmont Shore](/Belmont_Shore,_Long_Beach,_California) is the only legal off-leash dog beach in Los Angeles County.

## Sports

### Grand Prix of Long Beach

The [Grand Prix of Long Beach](/Grand_Prix_of_Long_Beach) is the city's signature event. Since 1975, it has transformed the downtown streets into a high-speed racetrack. Originally a [Formula 5000](/Formula_5000) race, it briefly hosted [Formula One](/Formula_One) as the [United States Grand Prix West](/United_States_Grand_Prix_West) before becoming a mainstay of American open-wheel racing.

### Long Beach Marathon

Held every October, the Long Beach Marathon draws thousands of runners who traverse a course that winds through the city's beaches, neighborhoods, and the [Cal State Long Beach](/Cal_State_Long_Beach) campus.

### Surfing

Ironically, for a city named Long Beach, surfing is now a rare sight. California's surf scene arguably began here in 1911, and the city hosted the first National Surfing Championships in 1938. However, the construction of a 2.2-mile-long breakwater in 1949 to protect the [United States Pacific Fleet](/United_States_Pacific_Fleet) effectively killed the waves, reducing the once-mighty surf to "mere lake-like lapping." The fleet is long gone, but the breakwater remains, a source of ongoing debate and the subject of costly studies about its potential removal.

### College sports

[Long Beach State](/California_State_University,_Long_Beach)'s athletic teams, known as the [Beach](/Long_Beach_State_Beach) (and the baseball team officially nicknamed the Dirtbags), compete in a variety of NCAA sports. The city's other collegiate team is from [Long Beach City College](/Long_Beach_City_College).

### 2028 Summer Olympics

Long Beach is slated to play a significant role in the [2028 Summer Olympics](/2028_Summer_Olympics), hosting events such as [BMX racing](/BMX_racing), [water polo](/Water_polo), [triathlon](/Triathlon), and [sailing](/Sailing).

## Government

Long Beach operates as a California [charter city](/Charter_city) under a [mayor–council form of government](/Mayor%E2%80%93council_government). It is a full-service city, meaning it provides nearly all of its own [municipal services](/Municipal_services), including its own police, fire, water, gas, and health departments—a rarity in a county of [contract cities](/Contract_city). This stubborn self-reliance is a core part of the city's political identity.

On the state level, Long Beach is represented in the [California State Senate](/California_State_Senate) by Democrat [Lena Gonzalez](/Lena_Gonzalez) ([33rd district](/California%27s_33rd_State_Senate_district)) and in the [California State Assembly](/California_State_Assembly) by Democrats [Mike Gipson](/Mike_Gipson) ([65th district](/California%27s_65th_State_Assembly_district)) and [Josh Lowenthal](/Josh_Lowenthal) ([69th district](/California%27s_69th_State_Assembly_district)). In the [United States House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives), the city is split between [California's 42nd congressional district](/California%27s_42nd_congressional_district) (Rep. [Robert Garcia](/Robert_Garcia_(California_politician))) and the [44th district](/California%27s_44th_congressional_district) (Rep. [Nanette Barragán](/Nanette_Barrag%C3%A1n)).

Politically, the city leans heavily Democratic.

### Restrictions on registered sex offenders

In 2008, Long Beach enacted some of the most restrictive ordinances in California regarding [registered sex offenders](/Sex_offender_registries_in_the_United_States). The laws prohibit residency within 2,000 feet of any park, school, or daycare center, effectively zoning them out of over 96% of the city's residential areas. The ordinances also place severe restrictions on their movement and presence in public spaces.

## Education

### Primary and secondary schools

Most of the city is served by the [Long Beach Unified School District](/Long_Beach_Unified_School_District) (LBUSD), a large and highly regarded district. Its high schools include the renowned [Long Beach Polytechnic High School](/Long_Beach_Polytechnic_High_School) and [Wilson High School](/Woodrow_Wilson_Classical_High_School). Small portions of the city are served by the [ABC Unified School District](/ABC_Unified_School_District), [Paramount Unified School District](/Paramount_Unified_School_District), and [Los Angeles Unified School District](/Los_Angeles_Unified_School_District).

### Colleges and universities

Long Beach is home to two major public institutions of higher learning. [California State University, Long Beach](/California_State_University,_Long_Beach) (CSULB), founded in 1949, is a large comprehensive university known for its strong arts programs. [Long Beach City College](/Long_Beach_City_College) (LBCC), a community college established in 1927, serves students across two campuses.

## Transportation

### Ports and freight

The [Port of Long Beach](/Port_of_Long_Beach) is the city's economic and logistical core. It is the second busiest [seaport in the United States](/Port) and a critical link in the global supply chain, primarily serving trade with the [Pacific Rim](/Pacific_Rim). Rail service from the port is provided by [Union Pacific Railroad](/Union_Pacific_Railroad) and [BNSF Railway](/BNSF_Railway), utilizing the massive [Alameda Corridor](/Alameda_Corridor) rail trench to move goods inland.

The city also features the Long Beach Cruise Terminal, operated by [Carnival Corporation](/Carnival_Corporation_%26_plc), and the Catalina Landing, which provides daily ferry service via [Catalina Express](/Catalina_Express).

### Public transportation

Local bus service is provided by [Long Beach Transit](/Long_Beach_Transit). The backbone of the city's regional transit is the [Metro A Line](/A_Line_(Los_Angeles_Metro)) (formerly the Blue Line), a [light rail](/Light_rail) service operated by [LA Metro](/Los_Angeles_County_Metropolitan_Transportation_Authority) that connects downtown Long Beach to downtown Los Angeles and beyond, tracing the route of the historic [Pacific Electric](/Pacific_Electric) [Long Beach Line](/Long_Beach_Line).

### Airports

[Long Beach Airport](/Long_Beach_Airport) (LGB) is a convenient regional airport known for its historic Art Deco terminal. For international flights, residents typically use [Los Angeles International Airport](/Los_Angeles_International_Airport) (LAX), located about 20 miles to the west.

### Freeways and highways

Long Beach is enmeshed in Southern California's freeway network. The [San Diego Freeway (I-405)](/Interstate_405_(California)) cuts across the city, while the [Long Beach Freeway (I-710)](/Interstate_710_and_State_Route_710) serves as a primary route for both commuters and the endless stream of trucks from the port. Other major arteries include the [San Gabriel River Freeway (I-605)](/Interstate_605) and the [Artesia Freeway (SR 91)](/California_State_Route_91).

## Media

The city's primary daily newspaper is the [Long Beach Press-Telegram](/Long_Beach_Press-Telegram). In 2013, the [Orange County Register](/Orange_County_Register) launched a short-lived daily competitor, the Long Beach Register, which folded after only sixteen months. The city is also served by several weekly papers and a growing number of online news outlets, including the *Long Beach Post* and *LBReport.com*.

## In popular culture

Thanks to its diverse architecture, varied neighborhoods, and proximity to Hollywood, Long Beach has served as a filming location for countless movies, television shows, and commercials. It is a cinematic chameleon, standing in for locations as varied as Miami ([CSI: Miami](/CSI:_Miami), [Dexter](/Dexter_(TV_series))), Chicago ([Ferris Bueller's Day Off](/Ferris_Bueller%27s_Day_Off)), and various anonymous urban landscapes for car chases in films like [Gone in 60 Seconds](/Gone_in_60_Seconds_(2000_film)) and [Speed](/Speed_(1994_film)). Local high schools, particularly [Long Beach Polytechnic High School](/Long_Beach_Polytechnic_High_School) and [Juan Rodriguez Cabrillo High School](/Cabrillo_High_School_(Long_Beach,_California)) (a primary location for [Glee](/Glee_(TV_series))), are frequently used. The city's ability to be anywhere has made it a go-to backlot for the entertainment industry.

